  "description": "Day 2 economic impact simulation: if internet went dark locally, United States would lose $8.45B/day; world $28.91B/day.",
  "excerpt": "2026-03-01 / day 2: a same-length local internet blackout simulation for the world and top economies, with United States and China leading the modeled daily losses and the world scenario at $28.91B/day.",
  "body_paragraphs": [
    "This post does not say these economies are currently losing money because Iran is offline. It uses Iran's blackout duration as a time clock and simulates what a same-length domestic internet blackout would cost each economy on day 2.",
    "Under the world scenario, a blackout of this length implies $28.91B in daily GDP loss and $54.31B in cumulative loss since day 1.",
    "For the large-economy scenarios, the biggest simulated daily losses today are: United States: $8.45B/day; China: $4.54B/day; Germany: $1.23B/day.",
    "Method: 2025 nominal GDP baseline × country-specific digital sensitivity coefficient × an outage-duration escalation curve that gets harsher as the blackout continues."
